The correct way to derive the volume of a pyramid using integration is by setting up the following:
We want to integrate the cross sectional area across the height of the pyramid. The cross section is nothing but a square so x*y. But x and y are a function of z. The slope of each are the same, 3-z, z being the height. Maximum dimensions at the base, and 0 at the top. So the integral will be

S(x(z) * y(z)) dz
Which is nothing but
S((z-3)*(z-3)) dz
S((z-3)^2) dz from 0 to 3 is 9. Which is what you would expect from the volume formula, lwh/3.
